	 						<h3><a href=making/index.html>MakerBot</a></h3>
	 						<p>The physics department purchased a MakerBot Thing-O-Matic in Dec. 2011. The physcs club assembled the printer, and manages its use. For more on what the bot can do, check out the recent <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2011/06/15/technology/personaltech/20110915-BASICS.html?src=tp">New York Times Article</a></p>
	 						<h3><a href="/maker">Making and Hacking</a></h3>
	 						<p>I am generally interested in all sorts of making and hacking. I teach electronics at Pacific, and this course has showed me how powerful the maker ethic is among students here. I don't think Pacific is unique in that sense... America has strayed from what made us great: ingenuity, creativity, and productivity. In the way that garage bands reshaped the 90's of my youth, I hope that garage factories reshape the manufacturing landscape of the next decade. I'll certainly be doing my part!</p>
